    skos:prefLabel "Business Rule Reconciliation with Policy"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6085> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "This presents the primary entities to model Business Rules as specifications of business guidelines that are expressed declaratively in condition-action terminology. The model below captures the entities to enable capture BusinessRules specification and enable model constraints for processes.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6085" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure BR.01 - Basic Business Rule"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6087> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "Following as a conceptual representation of BUSINESS RULE with related entities and the meanings to the relations is depicted. <br/>In the diagram,<br/><ul><li>BusinessRuleTrigerEvent - Represents an event or trigger that initiates the execution of a business rule. For example, when a specific condition occurs (e.g., a customer places an order), it triggers the associated rule to be invoked.</li></ul><ul><li>BusinessRule - Represents the specific business rule. It combines the events, conditions, and action components to formalize the full implications of the rule. The rule defines what should happen when certain conditions are met, and the consequences of those conditions being met might be more than one action.</li></ul><ul><li>BusinessRuleCondition - This represents the logical conditions that must be satisfied for the rule to execute. Conditions evaluate specific criteria (e.g., “If the order total exceeds $100”). Multiple conditions can be associated with a single rule.</li></ul><ul><li>BusinessRuleAction - This defines the actions or consequences that occur when the rule is triggered. Actions can include operations like applying discounts, sending notifications, or updating data.</li></ul><ul><li>BusinessRuleConditionConstraint - This addresses the need to capture any additional constraints or criteria related to the conditions. Constraints are added refinement to the conditions (e.g., “Checks if the customer is a gold member”).</li></ul><p/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6087" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure BR.02 - Business Rule High Level Entity Model"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6089> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "Business Rule Action represents the executable component of a business rule, defining the operations that should be carried out when certain conditions are met. It is closely linked to the ‘Business Rule Condition’ class, as actions are contingent upon the evaluation of conditions. The class also has a relationship with the ‘Business Rule Trigger Event’ class, indicating that actions can be initiated by specific events (within a system). Business Rule Action plays a critical role in the operational aspect of business rules, translating conditions and events into tangible outcomes.<br/>In the broader context of this figure, the ‘Business Rule Action’ class is part of a complex network that includes specifications, constraints, and trigger events. This figure is meant to illustrate the interaction with immediate classes that support business rule management. Actions defined in the Business Rule class can be further detailed in the ‘Business Rule Action Specification’ class, which would provide additional information on how the actions are to be executed, emphasizing the modular and extensible nature of the model.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6089" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure BR.03 - Business Rule Action"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6091> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "The ‘Business Rule Condition’ figure illustrates reuse of the SID pattern, with inheritance from Entity/EntitySpec. The information captured to elaborate the decision-making elements within the business rule model. It encapsulates the logic that determines whether a business rule should be activated, based on the evaluation of specific criteria. The Business Rule Condition class is essential for the functioning of business rules, as it holds the expressions that are assessed to trigger corresponding actions. The figure shows the direct relationship with the ‘Business Rule’ class, indicating that each condition is an integral part of a business rule.<br/>Contextually, the ‘Business Rule Condition’ class is associated with groups, specifications, and constraints, which allow for the organization and detailed definition of conditions. Business Rule Conditions can be grouped, as in ‘Business Rule Condition Group’ and ‘Business Rule Condition Specification’ provides a means to specify grouping characteristics.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6091" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure BR.04 - Business Rule Condition"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6093> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "‘Business Rule Condition Constraint’ figure illustrates the use of the SID pattern with inheritance from Entity/EntitySpec pattern. The figure provides an overview of how information that establish limitations or restrictions on a Business Rule are applied to conditions within the business rule. ‘Business Rule Condition Constraint’ class ensures that the conditions under which business rules are executed are within specified parameters. Each constraint is specifically tied to a condition.<br/>From a contextual standpoint, and the ‘Business Rule Condition Constraint’ class is used to illustrate this structure. The relationship with ‘Business Rule Condition Constraint Specification’ and ‘Business Rule Condition Constraint Type’ classes provides a means to classify constraints.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6093" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure BR.05 - Business Rule Condition Constraint"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6095> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "The ‘Business Rule Trigger Event’ class represents information to capture events that initiate the evaluation of business rules. The figure shows reuse of SID pattern by way Entity/EntitySpec and information that captures the Business Rule Trigger Event Types and Unit. <br/>A business rule execution processes will link specific trigger occurrences to the activating rule. Business Rule Trigger Event is crucial for the dynamic aspect of business rules, as it allows to capture information that enable respond to real-time events and changes in the environment. <br/>In the wider context of the figure, the ‘Business Rule Trigger Event’ will capture event specifications, types, and windows and interact with the ‘Business Rule Trigger Event Specification’ class to detail the characteristics of events. ‘Business Rule Trigger Event Type’ and ‘Business Rule Trigger Event Window’ classes help to classify and time-bound events.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6095" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure BR.06 - Business Rule Trigger Event"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6097> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "Represents the information to capture the transactional process. This is an abstract representation of a task by way of an activity/workflow/Closedloopd etc.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6097" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure BR.07 - Detailed Business Rule"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6099> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "This diagram depicts types of business rules, including:<br/><ul><li>ActivityBusinessRule</li><li>PolicyBusinessRule</li><li>WorkflowBusinessRule</li><li>ClosedLoopBusinessRule</li></ul>Each of these will be further specified in other ABEs.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6099" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure BR.08 - Types of Business Rules"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6101> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "The business rule lifecycle illustration describes the systematic process for defining, creating, and managing business rules from inception to retirement. Initially, the PLAN stage involves defining the scope and objectives of the business rules. This is followed by the CREATE phase, where rules are specified and cataloged. Once created, rules are MAP(ped), which involves organizing them in relation to policies and linking them to their sources, such as `partyRole`, and associating them with relevant activities, workflows, or closed loops.<br/>The lifecycle continues with the TRANSFORM stage, where rules are formalized semantically, and if necessary, re-organized based on feedback. The TEST phase involves validating the rules to verify conditions and ensure integrity. Rules that pass the test are then APPLY(ied), which includes administering, activating, and assigning them to their respective activities or workflows. The ACTIVE stage is where rules are enforced, and they may cycle back through APPLY, TRANSFORM, or MAP if re-application, re-transformation, or re-mapping is needed. If a rule is suspended, it enters the INACTIVE state, where it can be modified, excepted, or expired. From the INACTIVE state, rules can be re-activated, re-mapped, or decommissioned, completing the lifecycle.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6101" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure BR.09 - Business Rule Management Lifecycle"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6103> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "The figure is an instance of the SID Business Rule Model which a generalized information model for all rules. The example captures information semantically distilled from the business rule statement which is given as ‘If a user is making an order check if they are over 17 years old, and if they have more than 5 orders as a new user, offer them 20% discount if their total order is between $100 and $200, and 30% discount if their total order is between $200 and $400 and when they have successful checkout the order enroll them into the loyalty service, and send them an email thanking them, otherwise send them an email if they aren't up to 18 years old.’ <br/>Based on this statement, the BusinessRule class captures the statement and relevant information to identify it's validity, start and end date. The entire statement outlines a set of conditions and actions based on user behavior and order details.<br/>The BusinessRuleCondition class identifies the conditions, including checking if the user is over 17 years old and if they have more than 5 orders as a new user etc..<br/>BusinessRuleAction identified in the statement include ‘offering a 20% discount’ for ‘orders between $100 and $200’, ‘a 30% discount for orders between $200 and $400’, ‘enrolling the user into the loyalty service’ after successful checkout, and ‘sending email’.<br/>BusinessRuleTriggerEvent captured events that enable trigger business rule, such as ‘user making an order’ and the successful ‘checkout’ of the order.<br/>BusinessRuleConditionConstraint: The constraints class captures the key constraints, such as the age limit (over 17 years old) and the order total being within specific ranges for the discounts to apply.<br/>These key ABEs/BEs represent components of the model that reflect how different elements like BusinessRule, BusinessRuleCondition, and BusinessRuleAction are used to define and manage business logic.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6103" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure BR.10 - Business Rule Example"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6106> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6105> ;
    skos:definition "build the rule(s)<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6106" ;
    skos:prefLabel "EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA18_EA1_EA6106"@en .

