    skos:definition "MaturityModelSpec represents the blueprint or detailed definition of a Maturity Model.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA1_EA6291" ;
    skos:prefLabel "MaturityModelSpecification"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6292> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6300> ;
    skos:definition "The figure presents a high-level conceptualization of a Maturity Model which illustrates a MaturityModel has a certain structure composed of MaturityModelCriteria organized by Goals. Criteria are defined in a maturity model and are evaluated within the context of MaturityModelDimensions, which may have sub-dimensions. The model also considers MaturityModelLevels, which are assessed through ScoringRubrics and can be used for ComplianceTagging. Assessments, known as PastAssessments, are conducted by a MaturityModelAssessor, potentially leading to GapAnalysisActions and recommended Activity.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6292" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure MMdlE.01 - Detailed Maturity Model"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6294> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6300> ;
    skos:definition "This state machine provides roadmap that captures the journey an entity takes to maturity. It is built on formal state machine concepts where the entuity is always in one of several distinct states: Initiating, Emerging, Performing, Advancing, or Leading. Each state represents a key phase in the entities maturity—from the early state to the top most state... in an exampel of digital maturity, from formulating your digital strategy (Initiating), through launching isolated projects (Emerging) and coordinating effective implementations (Performing), to delivering integrated outcomes (Advancing) and ultimately achieving a best‑in‑class position (Leading). Transitions between these states are driven by specific events. For example, when your digital strategy matures and pilot projects prove successful, the event labeled “mature” pushes the organization from Initiating to Emerging, whereas setbacks or resource issues might trigger a transition back or keep the organization in its current state.<br/><br/>This model isn’t strictly linear—it acknowledges that mautiryt can involve progress, pauses, and even setbacks. You will also notice a lack of a terminal state. In many state machine models—especially ones that represent continuous processes like digital maturity—there isn’t an explicit \"exit\" state. Instead, the design intentionally leaves the process open-ended to mean that No Final Terminal State to reinforce that there is always room for reassessment or further innovation. Also this is Cyclical and Adaptive state machine, more importantly for maturity models, they aren'y a sequence where you arrive, finish, and then stop. Instead, it’s cyclic—a best-in-class organization can encounter disruptive market changes, new technologies, or internal challenges that cause it to recalibrate. In our model, although the \"Leading\" state may look like the top rung, transitions from Leading to Advancing or even Leading to Performing are possible when conditions shift. This flexibility means that rather than “exiting” the process, organizations continuously revisit aspects of their digital initiatives to stay relevant and innovative.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6294" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure MMdlE.02 - Maturity Model State Machine"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6296> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6300> ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6296" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Delete Figure MMdlE.03 - Maturity Model Entity Lifecycle overview"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6298> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6300> ;
    skos:definition "Maturity Model Lifecycle is a comprehensive state model designed to assess, identify, plan, implement, monitor, and continuously improve the maturity levels of an organization’s capability/capabilities. It is a cyclical process that reemphasizes the purpose of a maturity as a journey of improvement, ensuring ongoing enhancements and optimizations of capabilities, processes, products, services and systems.<br/><br/>The lifecycle starts with a detailed assessment to evaluate the current maturity state, followed by identifying gaps and areas for improvement. Subsequently, an action plan is developed and implemented. The progress of these actions is monitored and evaluated, leading to continuous improvements. This iterative process helps organizations achieve their target maturity levels and sustain progress through ongoing evaluations and refinements.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA21_EA2_EA6298" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Delete Figure MMdlE.04 - Maturity Model Lifecycle"@en .

