<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4823> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "<b>Capacity and the Business Process Framework (eTOM)</b><br/>A number of eTOM Level 3 process elements were used as the basis for some of the requirements satisfied by this model. They include the L3 processes, Produce Product Portfolio Business Plans. Produce Service Business Plans, and Produce Resource Business Plans, with L1 Strategy processes. And, the L3 processes, Enable Service Configuration & Activation and Enable Resource Provisioning, within the L1 Operations Support & Readiness processes.<br/><br/>The model presented here shows both capacity and demand on capacity. Beginning with a description of a generalized model, specializations to support various types of capacity and demand are shown.<br/>There are several types (subclasses) of capacity as shown in the following Figure. For example, the requirement exists to be capable of delivering 10000 Products during the first week of June in the Northeast geographic area. This would be represented as an instance of ProductCapacity as shown in the figure. Capacity can be expressed in terms of planned or actual Capacity using the plannedOrActualCapacity attribute.<br/>The different types (subclasses) of Capacity can be related to one another. For example, ServiceCapacity may be used to calculate ResourceCapacity. Or, Capacity could be aggregated. The CapacityRelationship entity provides support for these and other inter-demand relationships.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4823" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.01 - Types of Capacity Entities"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4825> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "A generalized capacity and capacity demand model is shown in the following Figure.<br/>The need to satisfy the capacity requirement during the first week in June is expressed using the fromToDateTime attribute, which is a composite of from and to dates/times, and the rangeInterval attribute of ApplicableTimePeriod. Refinements to the schedule can include days of the week as shown by the daysOfWeek attribute in the ApplicableTimePeriod entity. The rangeInterval attribute is used to handle some combination of #gt;, #lt;, #gt;=, #lt;=. It is assumed this is a planned Capacity, which would be indicated using the plannedOrActutalCapacity attribute. The CapacityRelationship entity enables a planned Capacity to be associated with an actual Capacity or for Capacities to be aggregated.<br/>The requirement for this capacity to be available in the Northeast geographic area is expressed using the relationship to GeographicPlace. Other entities that further define/refine capacity requirements could be added as needed by extending the SID.<br/>The ability to deliver 10000 units of Product described in the previous example is expressed via the CapacityAmount, whose datatype is Quantity. Quantity is a composite of an amount attribute and a units (unit of measure) attribute. For this instance of Capacity, the capacityAmount attribute contains the amount “10000”, and the unit of measure “units”. Other examples of units of measure could be transaction volumes, storage requirements, traffic volumes, port availabilities, and so forth. The capacityAmountFrom, capacityAmountTo, and rangeInterval enable ranges of capacity to be specified.<br/>Demands are placed on the capacity as defined by the CapacityDemand entity. The related ApplicableTimePeriod is used to here to express the timeframe over which the demand exists. It may or may not be the same instance of the ApplicableTimePeriod associated with the Capacity. Therefore, it may be a demand placed on more than one CapacityAmount. Similarly, the CapacityAmount may have many demands placed against it.<br/>The attributes are similar to those in CapacityAmount with the addition of a priority attribute that defines the relative importance of this demand.<br/>The AppliedCapacityDemand entity represents the amount of the CapacityDemand that has been applied against a CapacityAmount.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4825" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.02 - Basic Capacity Entities"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4827> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "Similar to types (subclasses) of Capacity, there are types of CapacityDemand as shown in the following Figure. An example of each, Capacity and CapacityDemand will be described further in the next section.<br/>The different types (subclasses) of CapacityDemand can be related to one another. For example, ServiceCapacityDemand may be used to calculate ResourceCapacityDemand. Or, demand could be aggregated. The CapacityDemandRelationship entity provides support for these and other inter-demand relationships.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4827" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.03 - Types of Demand Entities"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4829> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "This section describes ResourceCapacity and ResourceCapacityDemand entities.<br/>A similar set of entities, not yet included in the model until some agreement is reached on the basic model and the ResourceCapacity and ResourceCapacityDemand, would support similar Product and Service capacity concepts.<br/>The following Figure shows that ResourceCapacity can be expressed in terms of types of Resources (ResourceSpecifications) or instances of Resources.<br/>There is often a need to express capacity (planned and unplanned) in a general way for all instances of a Resource, possibly within a specific Geographic Area. This is where ResourceCapacity would be related to ResourceSpecification. For example, the need for fiber across networks in the southwest quadrant of a city to connect up to 100 households.<br/>Similarly, there is often a need to express capacity for a specific instance of a Resource. For example, the western distribution network must support XXX Terabytes of bandwidth. This would be handled by the association between ResourceCapacity and Resource in the figure.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4829" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.04 - Basic Resource Capacity Entities"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4831> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "The following Figure shows ProductCapacity specific relationships.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4831" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.05 - Basic Product Capacity Entities"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4833> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "The following Figure shows ServiceCapacity specific relationships.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4833" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.06 - Basic Service Capacity Entities"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4835> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "CapacityDemand, in this case Resource CapacityDemand, can be reflected by / based upon associations to a number of other entities. In the following Figure, the entities shown represent these (there may be more that could be added to the model as needed by the Information Framework implementer using published extension guidelines) and related to ResourceCapacityDemand).<br/>In the figure, one Resource may place (require) a demand on another. For example, a Scheduler may demand that a network support one million queries a day.<br/>ServiceForecasts may also influence the capacity demands for Resources as described in various eTOM process elements. So, can ResourceForecasts. While this is acknowledged here, these two entities, which are most likely ABEs, have not been modeled as part of the Capacity Model that was contributed to the Information Framework.<br/>A single Service may also make a demand of ResourceCapacity. An important point to note is that care must be taken when determining demand so that none of the various sources of demand overlap with one another.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4835" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.07 - Basic Resource Demand Entities"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4837> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "The following Figure shows ProductCapacityDemand and its specific relationships.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4837" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.08 - Basic Product Demand Entities"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4839> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "The following Figure shows ServiceCapacityDemand and its specific relationships.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4839" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.09 - Basic Service Demand Entities"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4841> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">An example of dependencies is show in the following Figure. The capacity/demand relationships between resources would be used to determine the demand placed on the virtual resources by the three instances of Application A. And the relationships would then be used determine the demand placed on the physical resources by the virtual resources. This information is what could be used in part to support the policy-based load balancing described in the first example of this section.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4841" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.10 – Capacity Dependencies Example"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4843> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">There is most likely a need to provide the ability to calculate the demand placed on a Resource, or other demand entity, based on the source of the demand, such as a Service or other Resource. To support this requirement the current Characteristic model could be considered for use or additional entities that support the calculation could be identified and added to the Capacity model.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">One example use of the model is shown in the following Figure. Available capacity of the machines and an associated SID load balancing Policy would be used to identify that an application (APP1) should be dynamically moved to the machine with a large amount of available capacity. As a result, the demand placed on the first machine by APP1 would be removed from the first machine and transferred to represent demand on the second machine.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4843" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CM.11– Dynamic Load Balancing and Capacity Example"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4846> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4846" ;
    skos:prefLabel "EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4846"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4847> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4847" ;
    skos:prefLabel "EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4847"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4848> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "The period of time for which Capacity or CapacityDemand applies.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4848" ;
    skos:prefLabel "ApplicableTimePeriod"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4849> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "The amount of CapcityDemand applied to a CapacityAmount.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4849" ;
    skos:prefLabel "AppliedCapacityDemand"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4850> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "Specific ability of an entity measured in quantity and units of quantity over an extended period.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4850" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Capacity"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4851> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "A quantity that defines the Capacity.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4851" ;
    skos:prefLabel "CapacityAmount"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4852> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "The amount of capacity that is required, planned to be consumed or has been consumed.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4852" ;
    skos:prefLabel "CapacityDemand"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4853> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "A relationship between/among CapacityDemand.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4853" ;
    skos:prefLabel "CapacityDemandRelationship"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4854> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4845> ;
    skos:definition "A relationship between/among Capacity.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA6_EA4854" ;
    skos:prefLabel "CapacityRelationship"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4872> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:definition "The following Figure shows the addition of a FederatedCatalogSpecification and an EntityCatalogSpeciffication as subclasses of CatalogSpecification. Like the other types of CatalogSpecifications their content can be dynamically defined at run time. The EntityCatalogSpecification enables any catalog, such as the VNFCatalog mentioned in the Examples, to be defined. The FederatedCatalogSpecificationComprisedOf association enables any combination of the subclasses to be federated supporting the dynamic NFV Catalog Federation requirement in the Examples.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4872" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure EC.01 - Entity and Federated Catalog Specification"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4874> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:definition "The following Figure shows the Catalog and its subclasses that can be dynamically generated at run time based on their specification.<br/>An EntityCatalogItem can be one that is contained in a Product, Service, or Resource Catalog, or any Entity or EntitySpecification that has been included in the definition of its specification using the associations to EntitySpecificationType and/or PolicySet.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4874" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure EC.02 - Entity Catalog"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4876> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">The following example shows how a Broadband catalog can be specified and dynamically generated.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">Originally, vendor X’s catalog Broadband catalog only contained a physical gateway and phones for VoIP. But now the vendor wants to build a Broadband Procurement Catalog that contains any broadband offering that can be acquired. </font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">To be able to dynamically build / update the Catalog rules related to the corresponding CatalogSpecification are needed.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">The rules specify:</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">When the Catalog has to be updated by creating a triggering Event and relating it to the specification for the Broadband Procurement Catalog</font></li><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Which “category”, or ProductSpecificationType, and its related ProductSpecifications are to have their </font><font color=\"#29313b\">ProductOfferingSpecifications</font><font color=\"#29313b\">, is to be included in the catalog, by relating them to the specification for the Broadband Procurement Catalog.</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">The following Figure – Broadband Procurement Catalog shows the CatalogSpecification instance and Catalog instances and instances of their related entities. According to the rule specified for the Broadband Catalog Specification, a Broadband Procurement Catalog is first built in January; then another one is built in February. It contains all that can be acquired for a Virtualized Gateway, in addition to the Physical Gateway and the IP Phone. The example also illustrates that the “IP Phone” instance of ProductSpecification is related to two instances of ProductSpecificationType and therefore the corresponding </font><font color=\"#29313b\">ProductOfferingSpecification </font><font color=\"#29313b\">is available for inclusion in other catalogs</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4876" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure EC.02- I01 – Broadband Procurement Catalog"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4879> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:definition "EntityCatalogItem, ProdCatProdOffer, ServCatalogServCandidate, and ResCatalogResCandidate can collectively be called CatalogItem<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4879" ;
    skos:prefLabel "EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4879"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4880> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4880" ;
    skos:prefLabel "EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4880"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4881> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4881" ;
    skos:prefLabel "EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4881"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4882> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:definition "A relationship between Catalogs.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4882" ;
    skos:prefLabel "CatalogRelationship"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4883> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:definition "A collection of EntityCatalogItems.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4883" ;
    skos:prefLabel "EntityCatalog"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4884> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:definition "An item, such as an Entity, EntitySpecification, ProductOffering, ServiceCandidate, or ResourceCandidate that appears in a EntityCatalog.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4884" ;
    skos:prefLabel "EntityCatalogItem"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4885> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:definition "A set of basic facts that defines, or specifies, what an EntityCatalog is, such as its name, description, and so forth.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4885" ;
    skos:prefLabel "EntityCatalogSpecification"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4886> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:definition "A collection of two or more other Catalogs.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4886" ;
    skos:prefLabel "FederatedCatalog"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4887> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4878> ;
    skos:definition "A set of basic facts that defines, or specifies, what a FederatedCatalog is, such as its name, description, and so forth.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA1_EA4887" ;
    skos:prefLabel "FederatedCatalogSpecification"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4855> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4867> ;
    skos:definition "The Catalog ABE paragraph describes the usage of “Catalogs” to provide consistency of catalog model definitions across the Product, Service, and Resource domains, and to support the federation of catalogs and the ability to create a catalog containing any entity and/or its specification.<br/>A generalized Catalog ABE contains generic (abstract) CatalogSpecification and Catalog entities used to define types of catalog specifications and types of catalog entities. The patterns used to model Catalog business entities are the EntitySpecification/Entity and the CharacteristicSpecification/CharacteristicValue patterns. It also uses relationship entities as an alternate to the Composite/Atomic pattern. It embraces the existing entity of ‘Product Catalog ABE’ definition present before this guidebook was developed.<br/><br/>The CatalogSpecificationRelationship entity provides the ability to group specifications much like the Composite/Atomic pattern using the “type” attribute to specify that the relationship is a composite/atomic. For example, a Smart Home CatalogSpecification could be comprised of a Smart Home Security CatalogSpecification and a Smart Home Appliance CatalogSpecification. The “type” attribute can also be used to indicate that one CatalogSpecification supersedes another or is included with another.<br/>The content of associated Catalogs can be dynamically defined using relationship to EntitySpecificationType for simple rules and/or to PolicySet for more complex rules. EntitySpecificationType is a way to create categories of any specification entity to which it or its subclasses are related, such as a ProductSpecificationType which is a subclass of EntitySpecificationType. For example, a Smart Home Security ProductSpecificationType could be related to the Smart Home Security CatalogSpecification. This relationship would enable a Smart Home Security Catalog, in this case a ProductCatalog, to be dynamically created. If there are more complex rules, such as limiting the catalog to only containing ProductOfferingSpecifications that are in surplus status then a PolicySet could be defined to only include ProductOfferingSpecifications that have this status.<br/>The Characteristic pattern can be used to define dynamic attributes for any CatalogSpecification along with the attributes values for any Catalog. <br/>Basic entities related to a CatalogSpecification and relationships with the existing entities are shown in the Figure Cat.01 – Catalog Specification.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4855" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure Cat.01 – Catalog Specification"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4857> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4867> ;
    skos:definition "A CatalogSpecification defines one or many Catalogs. The business entities that inherit from catalog: are ProductCatalog, ServiceCatalog and ResourceCatalog, EntityCatalog, and FederatedCatalog. EntityCatalog and FederatedCatalog will be described in a later section of this guide book.<br/>The following Figure depicts the relationship of Catalog entities to the existing entities of information framework in the Product, Service and Resource domains. <br/>In this figure there are two more entities that are introduced through this guidebook. They are ServiceCandidate and ResourceCandidate. These two entities are defined to enable the respective specifications (ServiceSpecification and ResourceSpecification) to be available for inclusion in respective catalogs. As such the instances of “candidate” entities represent a subset of all the respective “specification” entities. For example, obsolete replacement ResourceSpecifications may not be of interest from a catalog perspective.<br/>The PartyRole who provides the Catalog can also be specified. For example, a Product Catalog provided by an application developer.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4857" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure Cat.02 – Catalog Entities and Associations"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4859> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4867> ;
    skos:definition "A ProductCatalog is a collection of ProductOfferingSpecifications, intended for a specific DistributionChannel, enhanced with additional information such as SLA parameters, invoicing and shipping details. As described in the Products addendum document, each ProductOfferingSpecification in a ProductCatalog combines pricing and availability information with ProductSpecifications that describe the relationships between Products, the Services used to realize the Products, and the Resources they require.<br/>An enterprise may choose to present its ProductOfferingSpecifications to multiple audiences through multiple channels. Therefore, although the collection of all available ProductOfferingSpecifications may be considered “the” ProductCatalog, the information model should support the definition and differentiation of multiple ProductCatalogs, containing possibly overlapping subsets of the ProductOfferingSpecification universe. <br/>A ProductOfferingSpecification may be “published” – made visible – in any number of ProductCatalogs, or in none. The most important association in the Product Catalog ABE is the publication of a ProductOfferingSpecification in a ProductCatalog. Attributes affecting that association, such as the time period during which a ProductOfferingSpecification is valid in a particular ProductCatalog, are contained in the association class ProdCatalogProdOffer.<br/>The ProductCatalog itself may have attributes that define its identity or existence, such as type (String) and validFor (TimePeriod). But most of the variant data related to a ProductCatalog is controlled by the ProductCatalogSpecification entity.<br/>Key associations with entities in other domains include a ProductCatalog’s availability through a SalesChannel, and the publication of a ProductCatalog in a GeographicArea. The availability of a ProductCatalog through a specific SalesChannel implies that each ProductOfferingPrice that values a ProductOfferingSpecification appearing in that ProductCatalog must also be made available through the same SalesChannel. In turn, each ProductOfferingPrice may be advertised in any number of ProdCatalogProdOffers.<br/>ProdCatalogProdOffer may contain additional information regarding the offering in the catalog, such as the location of an offering in a catalog. These basic entities are shown in the following Figure.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4859" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure Cat.03 – Product Catalog Definition and Basic Relationships"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4861> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4867> ;
    skos:definition "Several additional entities complete the Product Catalog. A DistributionChannel is responsible for providing ProductOfferingSpecifications in a specific GeographicArea. Each ProductOfferingSpecification is managed under a ProductOfferingStrategy that supports any number of MarketingCampaigns. MarketingCampaigns are run through SalesChannels, and use ProductCatalogs selected by ProductCatalogSpecification. These entities are shown in the following Figure.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4861" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure Cat.04 – Product Catalog Entities and Associations"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4863> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4867> ;
    skos:definition "A ServiceCatalog is a group of ServiceSpecifications made available through ServiceCandidates that an organization provides to the consumers (internal consumers like its employees or B2B customers or B2C customers). A ServiceCatalog typically includes name, description and time period that is valid for. It will have a list of ServiceCandidates. A ServiceCandidate is an entity that makes a ServiceSpecification available to a catalog. A ServiceCandidate and its associated ServiceSpecification may be “published” – made visible – in any number of ServiceCatalogs, or in none. One ServiceSpecification can be composed of other ServiceSpecifications. These ServiceSpecifications may also be published. Attributes affecting that association, such as the time period during which a ServiceCandidate is valid in a particular ServiceCatalog, are contained in the association class ServCatalogServCandidate. These basic entities are shown in the following Figure.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4863" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure Cat.05 – Service Catalog Entities and Associations"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4865> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4867> ;
    skos:definition "A ResourceCatalog is a list of ResourceSpecifications made available through ResourceCandidates that an organization will provide it to its consumers (internal or external). Not all ResourceCandidates are made available to a consumer. A ResourceCatalog typically includes name, description and time period that it is valid for. It will have a list of ResourceCandidates. A ResourceCandidate is an entity that enables the ResourceSpecifications to a catalog. A ResourceCandidate and its ResourceSpecification may be “published” – made visible – in any number of ResourceCatalogs, or in none. One ResourceSpecification can be composed of other ResourceSpecifications. These ResourceSpecifications may also be published. Attributes affecting that association, such as the time period during which a ResourceCandidate is valid in a particular ResourceCatalog, are contained in the association class ResCatalogResCandidate. These basic entities are shown in the following Figure.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4865" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure Cat.06 – Resource Catalog Entities and Associations"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4868> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4867> ;
    skos:definition "A catalog can be defined as a collation of items and arranging them in a particular manner based on the need. In the information framework point, it is as collection of entities. A catalog presentation can be in book form or web form.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4868" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Catalog"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4869> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4867> ;
    skos:definition "A set of basic facts that defines, or specifies, what a catalog is, such as its name, description, and so forth.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4869" ;
    skos:prefLabel "CatalogSpecification"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4870> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4867> ;
    skos:definition "A relationship between CatalogSpecifications.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA7_EA4870" ;
    skos:prefLabel "CatalogSpecificationRelationship"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4915> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">This section uses Object/Instance diagrams to illustrate how various scenarios are supported by the model. Creating a Configuration without a ConfigurationSpecification shows the class diagram with callouts showing instances that are used to show how an instance of a Configuration can be created without an associated ConfigurationSpecification.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">The Configuration and ConfigurationSpecification exist but are not associated at this point. </font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4915" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CI.01a - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism using Characteristics"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4917> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">Figure CI.02 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - Configuration With No Specification Using Characteristic shows how characteristics are used to assign values to an instance of a ResourceConfiguration directly without using an instance of ResourceConfigSpec.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4917" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CI.02 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - Configuration With No Specification Using Characteristic"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4919> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">CharacteristicValue instances are used for assigning values to:</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">A=1</font></li><li><font color=\"#29313b\">B=2</font></li><li><font color=\"#29313b\">C is not assigned a value.</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">Alternatively if the attributes A, B, and C are explicitly modeled as attributes of a Resource then an instance of the Resource can serve as a ResourceConfigSpec to assign values to A, B, and C for any other Resource that contains these attributes. Figure CI.03 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - Configuration with No Specification Using Resource shows an instance of a Resource used in this way.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4919" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CI.03 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - Configuration with No Specification Using Resource"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4921> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "Figure CI.04 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - Specification Using Characteristics shows an example of how characteristics can be used to define an instance of a ResourceConfigSpec.<br/><font color=\"#29313b\">CharacteristicValue instances are used for assigning values to:</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">A=1</font></li><li><font color=\"#29313b\">C=2</font></li><li><font color=\"#29313b\">D=4</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">E=dog</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4921" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CI.04 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - Specification Using Characteristics"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4923> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">Alternatively if the attributes A, C, D, and E are explicitly modeled as attributes of a Resource then an instance of Resource can serve as a ResourceConfigSpec to assign values to these attributes for any other Resource that contains these attributes. Figure CI.05 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - ConfigurationSpecificationification Using Resource Entity shows this use of a Resource and an instance of it.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4923" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CI.05 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - ConfigurationSpecificationification Using Resource Entity"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4925> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">Figure CI.06 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - ConfigurationSpecificationification Applied Using Characteristic shows an alternate technique using characteristics.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4925" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CI.06 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - ConfigurationSpecificationification Applied Using Characteristic"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4927> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">In the instance of ResourceConfiguration, C is now assigned the value of 2. Also, the instance is now assigned two new attributes (D and E) and associated values. Attribute B (not shown) remains as a simple characteristic related to the instance of Resource as shown in Figure CI.03 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - Configuration with No Specification Using Resource. But other characteristics (A, C, D, E) are removed and replaced by the ResourceConfigSpec shown in Figure CI.05 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - ConfigurationSpecificationification Using Resource Entity. A specific operation, such as auto apply / apply all, could be defined to do this.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">New attributes in the configuration entities, such as ResourceConfiguration cannot be created. This would require an “add column” command made to the database, which can have a major impact to the associated application(s) that use this entity. Figure CI.07 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - ConfigurationSpecificationification Applied Using Resource Entity shows an example of using a combination of characteristic instances and a Resource instance applied to create an instance of ResourceConfiguration.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4927" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CI.07 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - ConfigurationSpecification Applied Using Resource Entity"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4929> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">The Configuration is for ResourceInstance4. ResourceInstance3 plays the role of ResourceConfigSpec. A and C are explicit attributes of the Resource not shown in the figure. D and E are not explicit attributes of the Resource instance and therefore are represented as instances of characteristics associated to the instance of ResourceConfiguration.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">Note that the simpler alternative from an instance perspective would be to use the ConfigSpecCharUse entity shown in Figure CP.03 - Configuration Spec and Configuration Characteristics. This figure shows how characteristics can be used to set values for them, but also for explicitly modeled attributes. However, it does require an application to perform matching of the characteristic’s name value with an explicit attribute of an entity as mentioned in the description of the figure. So, the choice of which model capabilities to use is up to the discretion of the SID implementer.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4929" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Additional MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism Examples"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4931> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "The removal of the association is shown in Figure CI.08 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - Removing Association to ConfigurationSpecification. When removed, any changes to the ConfigurationSpecification will not change any Configs that had been based on the spec.<br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4931" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CI.08 - MTOSI TMD Profile Mechanism - Removing Association to ConfigurationSpecification"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4933> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\"><b>MTOSI TCA Profile Mechanism - 1</b></font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Current parameter values are in Configuration only</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;This can be done by setting explicit attributes in the Configuration or just using Characteristics and no ConfigurationSpecification#gt;#gt;</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Modification of a ConfigurationSpecification parameter value overwrites the associated parameter value in the Configuration</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;This can be done by applying a ConfigurationSpecification, that may consist of a spec with explicit attributes and with Characteristics#gt;#gt;</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">(Re-)setting pointer to ConfigurationSpecification overwrites all corresponding parameter values in Configuration</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;This can be done removing the association to existing ConfigurationSpecification with an operation (auto apply / remove all) and apply a new ConfigurationSpecification with an operation (auto apply / apply all#gt;#gt;</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\"><br/></font><font color=\"#29313b\"><b>MTOSI TCA Profile Mechanism - 2</b></font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Removing pointer from ConfigurationSpecification does not change parameter values in Configuration</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;This can be done via an operation (auto apply / remove association only) between ConfigurationSpecification and Configuration#gt;#gt;</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">ConfigurationSpecification can have more parameters than Configuration</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;This can be done via an operation (manually apply / select ConfigurationSpecification attributes#gt;#gt;</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Configuration can have more parameters than ConfigurationSpecification</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;This can be done using various operations, such as using Characteristic without a ConfigurationSpecification, then applying a ConfigurationSpecification that has fewer equivalent attributes #gt;#gt;</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Same as the TMD pattern except that there is no Verify Assignment operation in this case</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;Since this appears to be a comment no explanation of how the model supports this is necessary#gt;#gt;</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\"><br/></font><font color=\"#29313b\"><b>MTOSI ASA Profile Mechanism</b></font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Current parameter values are in ConfigurationSpecification only</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;This can be done via an operation (auto apply / associate only) or (manually apply / associate only) or an attribute#gt;#gt;</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Modification of a ConfigurationSpecification parameter changes behavior of Configuration immediately</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;Explained on earlier slide#gt;#gt;</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Removing pointer to Profile removes all parameters from Configuration</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;Explained on earlier slide#gt;#gt;</font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">This is similar to Characteristic Specifications and Characteristic Specification Values in the SID model.</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;Since this appears to be a comment no explanation of how the model supports this is necessary#gt;#gt;</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">#lt;#lt;This can be done via an operation (auto apply / associate only) or (manually apply / associate only) or an attribute#gt;#gt; - mentioned on last diagram</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\"><b>MTOSI TC Profile Mechanism</b></font><br/><ul><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Current parameter values are in ConfigurationSpecification only</font></li><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Modification of a ConfigurationSpecification parameter changes behavior of Configuration immediately</font></li><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Removing pointer to ConfigurationSpecification removes all traffic conditioning from Configuration (for this frame grouping)</font></li></ul><font color=\"#29313b\">This case is more complex in that the Configuration has a transmission parameter which is essentially a table. Based on various characteristics, each row of the table points to a different ConfigurationSpecification</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4933" ;
    skos:prefLabel "MTOSI ASA Profile Mechanisms"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4935> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4935" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Traffic Map Table"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4937> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">Only the constraint model that supports this (Policy is another option as mentioned earlier) is shown in the figure below.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4937" ;
    skos:prefLabel "MTOSI TC Profile Mechanism – Model Support"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4939> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">Shown in the next figure is an example of how the constraint portion of the model supports the selection of profile #52 (ConfigurationSpecification) and an EntitySpecCharValueUse traffic class of 0.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4939" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Traffic Map Table Detail"@en .

<http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4941> a skos:Concept ;
    skos:broader <http://ots.local/thesaurus/sid/sid_EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4943> ;
    skos:definition "<font color=\"#29313b\">Constraint #1 – IF ConfigSpecConstraintMembersVLAN ID = 1000 and (Priority #gt;=0 or Priority #lt;=1) and Inner VLAN ID = 10 and (Inner Priority #gt;=0 or Inner Priority #lt;=3) …the relationship to the constraint is to ConfigurationSpecification 52 and EntitySpecCharValueUse traffic class value of 0</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">Shown in Figure CI.09 - MTOSI TC Profile Mechanism Constraint is the beginning of the constraint defined in the figure on the previous page along with the ResourceConfigSpec determined by the constraint and the ConfigurationSpec ‘s associated EntitySpecCharValueUse determined by the constraint.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\"><br/></font><font color=\"#29313b\">All requirements below are supported by the model as they are similar to other requirements for which support has been demonstrated in this slide set.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">ConfigurationSpecification Configuration Relationship Examples.</font><br/><ol><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Imposing a ValueRange with Attribute Value Track</font></li></ol><font color=\"#29313b\">An instance of a Service with a given VLAN ID being imposed on all the resources on which the service is running. The VLANID used is constrained within a given range as determined by the VLAN Pools</font><br/><ol><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Imposing a ValueRange with No Attribute Value Track.</font></li></ol><font color=\"#29313b\">Allocating a given customer a certain bandwidth within a VRF.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">This bandwidth will be constrained to a range depending on the bandwidth available at the core TE Tunnels. Once applied these are long-lived configurations per the business contract and therefore the attribute values do not track.</font><br/><ol><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Applied Values can be changed only via ConfigurationSpecification</font></li></ol><font color=\"#29313b\">ConfigurationSpecification has a generator logic within it and interacts with a number inventory to generate the appropriate RouteConfiguration imports and exports that form a given topology such as hub and spoke.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">Only the ConfigurationSpecification accesses the number inventory and therefore this attribute (or set of attributes) can only be changed via the ConfigurationSpecification.</font><br/><ol><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Applied ConfigurationSpecification that can be changed later by the ConfigurationSpecification.</font></li></ol><font color=\"#29313b\">ConfigurationSpecification.</font><br/><font color=\"#29313b\">Provisioning Bandwidth on Demand where in the morning the customer subscribes to increased bandwidth and in the night a lesser bandwidth. Both being effected in a scheduled, periodic manner by the ConfigurationSpecification.</font><br/><ol><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Pointer changed from one ConfigurationSpecification to the Other.</font></li></ol><font color=\"#29313b\">In a Discovery Module, certain parameters for a given vendor will be supported by MIBs while for another the same would be supported by a CLI command. To discover and stitch a service depending on the vendor being discovered during the process, the pointer may point to one ConfigurationSpecification or the other. </font><br/><ol><li><font color=\"#29313b\">Configuration having more attributes than ConfigurationSpecification and Configuration having more attributes than ConfigurationSpecification. [Slide 14 of Bernd]</font></li></ol><font color=\"#29313b\">CTP proxied with OAM Parameters, the OAM parameter do not belong Per-Se within the Configuration and the attributes that belong to the CTP do not appear in the Configuration.</font><br/>"@en ;
    skos:inScheme thes:sid ;
    skos:notation "sid:EARoot_EA4_EA2_EA10_EA8_EA1_EA4941" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Figure CI.09 - MTOSI TC Profile Mechanism Constraint"@en .

